{"text": "Exercise 3.1. Show that the Euler-Lagrange equations resulting from the action (3.4)\n\ngive the usual equations of relativistic particle kinematics:\n\n\u0307p\u03bd = 0 ,\n\np\u03bd =\n\nm \u0307x\u03bd\n\np\u2212 \u0307x\u03bc \u0307x\u03bc\n\n.\n\nReparametrization Invariance\n\nThe Einstein constraint p2 \u2261p\u03bc p\u03bc = \u2212m2 on the classical trajectories of the particle\n\n(Exercise 3.1) is related to the fact that the action (3.4) is invariant under arbitrary, local\n\nreparametrizations of the worldline, i.e.\n\n\u03c4 7\u2212\u2192\u03c4(\u03c4 \u2032) ,\n\nd\u03c4\n\nd\u03c4 \u2032 > 0 .\n\n(3.6)\n\nThis is a kind of local worldline \u201cgauge invariance\u201d which means that the form of S[x] is un-\n\nchanged under such a coordinate change, since d\u03c4\n\np\n\n\u2212 \u0307x\u03bc(\u03c4) \u0307x\u03bc(\u03c4) = d\u03c4 \u2032 p\n\n\u2212 \u0307x\u03bc(\u03c4 \u2032) \u0307x\u03bc(\u03c4 \u2032).\n\nIt is a one-dimensional version of the usual four-dimensional general coordinate invari-\n\nance in general relativity, in the sense that it corresponds to a worldline diffeomorphism\n\nsymmetry of the theory. An application of the standard Noether procedure to the 0+1-\n\ndimensional field theory (3.4) leads to a conserved Noether current whose continuity\n\nequation is precisely the constraint p2 = \u2212m2. It tells us how to eliminate one of the\n\np\u03bc\u2019s, and in the quantum theory it becomes the requirement that physical states and\n\nobservables must be gauge invariant. It enables us to select a suitable gauge. Let us look\n\nat a couple of simple examples, as this point will be crucial for our later generalizations.\n\n11\n\nExamples\n\n(1) Static Gauge : Here we take the gauge choice\n\nx0 = \u03c4 \u2261t\n\n(3.7)\n\nin which the action assumes the simple form\n\nS[x] = \u2212m\n\nZ\n\ndt\n\n\u221a\n\n1 \u2212v2\n\n(3.8)\n\nwhere\n\n\u20d7v = d\u20d7x\n\ndt\n\n(3.9)\n\nis the velocity of the particle.", "embedding": [0